# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-phosphoglyceric-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/1-3-bisphosphoglycerate] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/2-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/3-phosphoglycerate] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] The protein encoded by this gene is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P) and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes, are differentially expressed during development.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Aldolase A is found in the developing embryo and is produced in even greater amounts in adult muscle.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Aldolase A expression is repressed in adult liver, kidney and intestine and similar to aldolase C levels in brain and other nervous tissue.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Aldolase A deficiency has been associated with myopathy and hemolytic anemia.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Alternative splicing and alternative promoter usage results in multiple transcript variants.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Related pseudogenes have been identified on chromosomes 3 and 10.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA is a homotetramer and one of the three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] The *ALDOA* gene contains 8 exons and the 5' UTR IB.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Key amino acids responsible for its catalytic function have been identified.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] The residue Tyr363 functions as the acid–base catalyst for protonating C3 of the substrate, while Lys146 is proposed to stabilize the negative charge of the resulting conjugate base of Tyr363 and the strained configuration of the C-terminal.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Residue Glu187 participates in multiple functions, including FBP aldolase catalysis, acid–base catalysis during substrate binding, dehydration, and substrate cleavage.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Though ALDOA localizes to the nucleus, it lacks any known nuclear localization signals (NLS).
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] In mammalian aldolase, the key catalytic amino acid residues involved in the reaction are lysine and tyrosine.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] The tyrosine acts as an efficient hydrogen acceptor while the lysine covalently binds and stabilizes the intermediates.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Many bacteria use two magnesium ions in place of the lysine.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Compound C05378 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Enzyme 4.1.2.13 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Compound C00111 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA is a key enzyme in the fourth step of glycolysis, as well as in the reverse pathway gluconeogenesis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] It catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehydes-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate by aldol cleavage of the C3–C4 bond.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] As a result, it is a crucial player in ATP biosynthesis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA also contributes to other "moonlighting" functions such as muscle maintenance, regulation of cell shape and motility, striated muscle contraction, actin cytoskeleton organization, and regulation of cell proliferation.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA likely regulates actin cytoskeleton remodeling through interacting with cytohesin-2 (ARNO) and Arf6.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA is ubiquitously expressed in most tissues, though it is predominantly expressed in developing embryo and adult muscle.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] In lymphocytes, ALDOA is the predominant aldolase isoform.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Within the cell, ALDOA typically localizes to the cytoplasm, but it can localize to the nucleus during DNA synthesis of the cell cycle S phase.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] This nuclear localization is regulated by the protein kinases AKT and p38.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] It is suggested that the nucleus serves as a reservoir for ALDOA in low glucose conditions.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA has also been found in mitochondria.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] ALDOA is regulated by the energy metabolism substrates glucose, lactate, and glutamine.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] In human mast cells (MCs), ALDOA has been observed to undergo post-translational regulation by protein tyrosine nitration, which may alter its relative affinity for FBP and/or IP3.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] This change then affects IP3 and PLC signaling cascades in IgE-dependent responses.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Aldolase A (ALDOA) is highly expressed in multiple cancers, including lung squamous cell carcinoma (LSCC), renal cancer, and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] It is proposed that ALDOA overexpression enhances glycolysis in these tumor cells, promoting their growth.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] In LSCC, its upregulation correlates with metastasis and poor prognosis, while its downregulation reduces tumor cell motility and tumorigenesis.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Thus, ALDOA could be a potential LSCC biomarker and therapeutic drug target.
[src:2-phosphoglyceric-acid/aldolase-a] Aldolase A deficiency is a rare, autosomal recessive disorder that is linked to hemolysis and accompanied by weakness, muscle pain, and myopathy.
